John Edward: Linguistic Competence is Essential for World Citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a trajectory of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another series of excellent exam results, which is reinforced with individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community efforts.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for later and higher education, for the career they choose and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a personalized school curriculum, we note that modern languages remain a very popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you will reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will come to his heart.”
This is a very important reminder that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year’s exams, we can see that languages lead the ranking tables with the highest qualifications in independent schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained a higher A grade.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools reflected that 72% of students obtained a higher A rating in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of Spanish students also obtained an A rating.
This demonstrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital competencies that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, languages, as a subject of choice, are kept in the same consideration as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in study plans from independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK’s Employment and Competence Commission revealed that for reasons given by employers to cover vacancies, 17% was attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
As there are more and more potential job opportunities that require languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future with a permanent competition like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 survey by YouGov among more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation, and French, with 15% of speakers, was the only language with a double-digit percentage.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is important for today’s children.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developed economies, will give children better opportunities to find an important job.
In Scotland, there is diversity among schools in terms of the languages they are taught.
Some schools focus more on more traditional modern languages, while others teach languages that are deemed to be more important for the UK in the future by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, they will always be able to choose from a number of languages in independent schools, which have specialized teaching staff in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, regardless of what the future holds.
In the global commercial environment of the present era, it cannot be denied that languages remain vital to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be considered "international communicative competences".
Independent schools will continue to offer this option, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
