Harvard students take a course on resting habits.
This year, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep more, in an attempt to combat the ever-expanding culture of studying overnight, stimulated by caffeine.
One academic noted that often the number one university or the world’s students are dissatisfied with what goes into the basics about how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after giving a talk about the impact that sleep deprivation had on learning.
“At the end of the conversation, a girl approached me and said, ‘Why are they calling me now, all of this, in my last year?’
He said no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
In the course, implemented for the first time this year, students are explained the basic concepts on how good habits of sleep improve academic and sports performance, in addition to general well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after learning that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The course, one hour in duration, includes a number of interactive tasks.
In a section there is an image of a bedroom, where students have to click on coffee mugs, curtains, bamboo and books to receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, on how it affects sports performance in lack of sleep, and on the importance of maintaining a sleep routine.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Below, a map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily route.
“We know that the behavior of the students will not change immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know, as one has the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” said Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride to stay awake all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure that students suffer make sleep deprivation an ever-growing problem.
Ensuring that you enjoy good quality sleep for a long time should be a “secret weapon” for students to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he added, even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in annihilation mode and always makes them study.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies Chemistry and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
Raymond commented that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote the course throughout the campus.
The next step, he expects, is to ask postgraduate students to undertake a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students take into account the fact of setting an alarm when they go to sleep and when they wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can alter the harmoniousness of laughter.
