Red tide update: concentrations are reduced to Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tidal concentrations in certain parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more widespread proliferation conditions are being reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, suggesting a lower concentration.
The proliferation of the red tide extends along approximately 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to the counties of southern Lee.
Spots can be found 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places, compared to last week's situation.
The red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Mean concentrations on the coast or away from the coast have been reported in Pinellas County over the past week, concentrations of lows at highs at a distance from the coast in Hillsborough County, concentrations of funds or highs as lows in Manatee County, concentrations of funds at mid-costs in Manatee County, and concentrations of funds at mid-costs in Chartone County.
Respiratory irritations continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation has been reported over the past week in northeastern Florida.
